The kube scheduler, and the kube controller manager. Two control plane workhorses you have already met.

First, the kube scheduler, a recap from notebook seven. It watches pending pods, filters and scores the nodes, and binds the pod to the winning node. It is pluggable via scheduling profiles. It runs as a static pod, and it talks to the ay-pee-eye server, never to nodes directly.

Second, the kube controller manager. It is a single binary that hosts roughly thirty distinct controllers, each running the same observe, compare, act loop you have seen throughout this course. The ones that matter most. The node controller marks nodes not ready when they stop heart-beating, and manages no execute taints. The deployment and replica set controllers handle rollouts and match the pod count. The daemon set, stateful set, job, and cron job controllers manage their pods. The endpoints controller maintains the ready pod addresses behind each service. The service account controller creates a default account and token per namespace. The namespace controller cascades deletes when a namespace is terminating. The volume binder matches claims to volumes. And the horizontal pod autoscaler adjusts replicas by metrics.

Bundling them in one binary is just packaging. Each controller logically runs on its own. And they elect a leader, using a lease object in the kube system namespace, so only one instance is active at a time, even when the binary runs highly available across several control plane nodes.

And third, the cloud controller manager. The cloud specific bits were split out, so non cloud clusters do not need them. It runs the cloud side node controller, the route controller for pod networking, and the service controller, which provisions cloud load balancers for load balancer type services. On kind, with no cloud, it is not running at all. On our map, these are the kube scheduler and controller manager components. The decide and reconcile half of the control plane.
